    <node id="Content: Well, Suzy, following the vote, I was very keen that we work very closely with colleagues in higher education and further education, to get an understanding from on the ground about the potential impact. So, in terms of preparedness, we started that group in the September, and that work from that group, which includes both HE and FE, has been instrumental in helping the Government form its views, which were articulated in the Government's White Paper, 'Securing Wales' Future'. There has been ongoing work being done—as the debate in London and Europe becomes a little bit more clear, then it becomes a little less clear, and then a little bit more clear, but, bearing in mind the difficulties of working in an ever-changing field, we have been refining those approaches. Each institution has been looking at their own institution, because, as you can imagine, although we have an overview of the sector, the challenges are very different for individual institutions—so their exposure, for instance, to the number of European Union students that they have at their college, or the work that they might be doing with Horizon 2020, or their success—and there has been considerable success in the HE field in securing structural funds for various projects—the exposure and the potential" />
    <node id="1. Based on the provided transcript, the Welsh Government is taking several steps to ensure the sustainability of higher and further education despite the current managed deficit and uncertainty around future funding due to Brexit. These efforts include:&#10;&#10;a) Implementing the Diamond Review Proposals: The Welsh Government is committed to implementing the Diamond review proposals, which aim to move towards a more sustainable funding settlement for the higher education sector. They have shared their expectations with HEFCW regarding the implementation of Diamond and its impact on grant funding.&#10;&#10;b) Discussing Reid Review Implementation: Although no specific funding commitment has been made for the Reid review recommendations, the Welsh Government is actively discussing how to implement them within the government. The Reid review also focuses on creating a more sustainable funding model for higher education.&#10;&#10;c) Engaging with Higher Education Institutions and Stakeholders: Kirsty Williams AM and Eluned Morgan AM have joined the committee meeting to discuss the impact of Brexit on higher and further education, highlighting their close collaboration with the sector and student voice representatives to prepare for a potential 'no deal' Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;d) Securing Funds from European Transition Fund: The Welsh Government is accessing resources under the European Transition Fund, Global Wales program, and other opportunities within the EU transition pot of money to boost international marketing of the higher education sector and highlight its strengths. These efforts aim to attract more international students, providing additional revenue for institutions.&#10;&#10;e) Addressing Brexit-related Concerns: Although no specific funding commitment has been made, officials are aware that most higher education activities are secured until December 2020 under a 'no-deal' scenario. They are also working to address the uncertainty around research and apprenticeship provision beyond 2020, which may be affected by the broader economy and ability to work with companies locally and internationally due to the relationship with the EU.&#10;&#10;In summary, while the Welsh Government has not provided a specific funding commitment for higher and further education post-Brexit, they are taking various steps to ensure its sustainability through implementing review proposals, engaging with stakeholders, and securing alternative funds." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government has been engaging with both higher education (HE) and further education (FE) institutions regarding their preparedness for a potential &quot;no deal&quot; Brexit scenario.&#10;2. For HE institutions, officials have visited individual institutions to discuss their preparedness for a &quot;no deal&quot; Brexit. Funding for most HE activities is secured until December 2020 under this scenario.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is also working closely with the HE sector, Universities Wales, and student voice representatives to ensure that Wales's institutions are open for business and welcome both EU and international students. They are improving international marketing of the HE sector and accessing resources under the European Transition Fund, Global Wales program, and other opportunities within the EU transition pot of money to boost international marketing of the HE sector and highlight its strengths.&#10;4. While there is no specific information provided about visits to FE institutions or funding secured for FE activities in the given transcripts, it can be inferred that similar engagements have taken place or are planned for FE institutions, as the Welsh Government's actions cover both HE and FE sectors.&#10;5. Overall, the Welsh Government appears to be proactive in engaging with both HE and FE institutions to discuss Brexit preparedness and ensure continued operations in a &quot;no deal&quot; scenario." />
