    <node id="1. Quality of faculty: Both NUS and students are concerned about maintaining the quality of faculty in higher education institutions. They value the diversity and strength that EU staff bring to these institutions, making up around 11% of the faculty. They want assurance that there will be no negative impact on this valuable contribution and are working towards providing security and stability for EU staff.&#10;2. Diversity among student population: NUS and students also value diversity in the student population and want to ensure that European students feel secure about their funding for the next academic year, despite the uncertainty caused by Brexit.&#10;3. Participation in higher education schemes: NUS has launched a powerful campaign emphasizing the importance of Erasmus+ arrangements for Welsh students and young people. They believe there is a lot to be gained from participating in such programs, as many politicians have had the opportunity to study abroad themselves.&#10;&#10;In summary, NUS and students are concerned with preserving and enhancing the quality of higher education by maintaining faculty diversity, ensuring funding security for European students, and promoting participation in beneficial schemes like Erasmus+." />
    <node id=" and the student voice, about the importance of participation in that scheme.  NUS are also very concerned that there should be no negative impact on the quality of faculty. Our HE institutions, to a greater extent than FE, have faculty staff from the EU—it runs at about 11 per cent. That adds great diversity and strength to the quality of teaching within our institutions. Clearly, that is a concern for students. They want to have the best teachers, they want access to the best learning opportunities, and we've been very clear about the importance of providing security and stability for those staff, making sure we send very clear messages that they're very welcome and we value their contribution. NUS, again, also value the diversity in the student population. Again, as far as we've been able to, we've been able to give messages about the security of funding for European students for the next academic year. I wish I could go further, but that's out of my hands. We're working to the limits of what I feel comfortable in being able to guarantee without further guarantees from Westminster. So, we've been working closely with the student voice, and I think, Llyr, what's very clear is there is a consensus about what is important across the" />
    <node id="The European transition team serves as the central coordinating group responsible for overseeing the Welsh Government's preparations for transitioning out of the European Union. This team brings together representatives from various departments, including higher education and further education, to discuss and coordinate work on European transition. The team provides a governance structure for the Welsh Government, leading discussions with the Department for Exiting the European Union, No. 10, and the Joint Ministerial Committee, among other ministerial arrangements." />
    <node id="1. The current situation regarding ESF funding for FE colleges is that there is funding guaranteed until 2020. However, the potential impact of Brexit beyond this point remains uncertain. Eluned Morgan AM mentioned that they are engaging with relevant parties to understand the potential impact on the apprenticeship program, which receives about £15 million a year from ESF commitments. The number of apprenticeships is expected to reach 100,000, but no explicit assurance has been given regarding the delivery of the apprenticeship program in its entirety beyond 2020.&#10;2. The Welsh Government is gathering information about the impact of ESF funding on FE institutions compared to HE institutions through one-to-one engagement and discussions with FE colleges, just as they have visited individual HE institutions to discuss Brexit preparedness. While there is no specific mention of visits to FE institutions in the transcripts, it can be inferred that similar engagements are taking place for FE institutions to ensure their readiness for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario." />
    <node id=" they see things developing. I think it's quite a different response than what is going to be happening in HE.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Yes, because the student thing isn't such an issue, is it?&#10;Speaker: Eluned Morgan AM&#10;Content: You've got to remember that the FE colleges are much more anchored within their communities, they're much more localised, and so, for example, the number of EU students in these colleges is significantly lower. The number of staff in these colleges—I think they've analysed that there are only about 71 people. So, we're keeping in touch with them and we're letting them know what we are being told in terms of the Home Office settled status and what we can do to protect those 71. But that's a much bigger issue, I think, for higher education.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: What are they telling you about European social fund funding, though, because, as you say, they're locally anchored—the impact on FE of ESF funding is probably more significant than the issues we're talking about with higher education. How are you finding this out? Is this through one-to-one" />
    <node id="Based on the information provided in the transcripts, it is not possible to definitively say whether the UK government will maintain at least the current level of funding for Wales if they keep their Brexit commitments. Eluned Morgan AM indicates that maintaining the current level of funding would be a minimum, but the specific amount of funding was not mentioned in the transcript. Furthermore, the adequacy of this funding to address concerns about the shared prosperity fund is also not addressed. John Griffiths AM raises concerns about the shared prosperity fund and whether the UK government will follow through on commitments made during the Brexit referendum. Therefore, while maintaining at least the current level of funding would be a minimum, there are other aspects to consider, and the transcript does not provide enough information to provide a definitive answer." />
    <node id="1. Open for business and welcoming EU and international students: The Welsh Government, higher education institutions, and student voice representatives are working together to ensure clear messaging that Wales's institutions remain open for business and continue to welcome both EU and international students. This is crucial in maintaining and attracting a diverse student population.&#10;&#10;2. Fee levels for EU students: In the absence of a reciprocal arrangement agreement with the European Union under a 'no deal' Brexit scenario, higher education institutions in Wales would still have the ability to charge international fees to students from the EU. This is due to the UK government's control over its own immigration policy and the setting of different fee levels for students coming from different countries.&#10;&#10;3. Risk assessment and mitigation: The Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW) has conducted specific risk assessment and mitigation work regarding Brexit, although the extent of sharing this information publicly is at their discretion.&#10;&#10;4. Proactive institution visits: Welsh officials have been visiting individual higher education institutions (HEIs) to discuss their preparedness for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario, ensuring they have plans in place to deal with various potential outcomes.&#10;&#10;5. International marketing and research funding: The Welsh Government has collaborated with Universities Wales and student voice representatives to improve international marketing of the HE sector, access resources under the European Transition Fund, Global Wales program, and other EU transition pot opportunities to strengthen the sector's competitiveness in research funding, regardless of a deal or no-deal Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;6. Addressing issues related to Erasmus+ provision, Horizon 2020 impacts, and UK stand-alone projects: Welsh officials have been working with Westminster counterparts to tackle issues related to Erasmus+ provision, Horizon 2020 impacts, and UK stand-alone projects in the event of a 'no deal' Brexit.&#10;&#10;7. Comprehensive understanding of potential challenges: The Welsh Government has conducted its own analysis on the impact of Brexit on HE, FE, and apprenticeship provision, complementing Cardiff University's research with Bevan Foundation and others to provide a comprehensive understanding of potential challenges.&#10;&#10;8. Separate immigration policy for international students: Kirsty Williams AM is actively pushing for a separate immigration policy for international students, arguing that they should not be included in general immigration targets. She has also campaigned for post-study work visas to be made available to more institutions outside of the south-east of England, including Cardiff and Trinity Saint David.&#10;&#10;9. Maintaining quality of faculty: NUS and students are concerned about maintaining the quality of faculty in higher education institutions, valuing the diversity and strength that EU staff bring to these institutions. They want assurance that there will be no negative impact on this valuable contribution and are working towards providing security and stability for EU staff.&#10;&#10;10. Funding security for European students: NUS and students also value diversity in the student population and want to ensure that European students feel secure about their funding for the next academic year, despite the uncertainty caused by Brexit.&#10;&#10;11. Participation in higher education schemes: NUS has launched a powerful campaign emphasizing the importance of Erasmus+ arrangements for Welsh students and young people, promoting participation in beneficial schemes like Erasmus+." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is implementing the Diamond Review Proposals, which aim to create a more sustainable funding settlement for higher education. They have shared their expectations with HEFCW regarding the implementation of Diamond and its impact on grant funding.&#10;2. Although no specific funding commitment has been made for the Reid review recommendations, the Welsh Government is actively discussing how to implement them within the government. The Reid review also focuses on creating a more sustainable funding model for higher education.&#10;3. Kirsty Williams AM and Eluned Morgan AM have joined committee meetings to discuss the impact of Brexit on higher and further education, highlighting their close collaboration with the sector and student voice representatives to prepare for a potential 'no deal' Brexit scenario.&#10;4. The Welsh Government is accessing resources under the European Transition Fund, Global Wales program, and other opportunities within the EU transition pot of money to boost international marketing of the higher education sector and attract more international students, providing additional revenue for institutions.&#10;5. Officials are working to address uncertainty around research and apprenticeship provision beyond 2020, which may be affected by the broader economy and ability to work with companies locally and internationally due to the relationship with the EU." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is taking several steps to prepare for the impact of Brexit on employment, particularly in high-risk sectors like agriculture. Eluned Morgan AM mentioned that she has been pushing to address risks in these sectors and ensuring their needs are met.&#10;2. Part of this preparation involves engaging with regional skills partnerships and employers to understand their requirements and respond accordingly. This approach helps ensure that employability programs align with employer needs, fostering collaboration between different parties.&#10;3. While the transcripts do not explicitly mention Brexit preparedness for agriculture or other high-risk sectors, it can be inferred that similar proactive measures are being taken as those described for HE and FE institutions. This includes visits to relevant organizations and discussions about Brexit impacts and mitigation strategies.&#10;4. As part of the employability program, there is a focus on ensuring that Further Education (FE) courses align with employer needs, which will help maintain learning opportunities within high-risk sectors in a 'no deal' Brexit scenario. The Welsh Government has also allocated £10 million to emphasize this aim and encourage the sector to respond to employer demands.&#10;5. Lastly, a review is underway regarding how FE is funded, which may lead to changes in resource allocation towards courses that align with identified skills gaps and employer needs, further integrating Brexit preparedness with the ongoing employability program." />
    <node id="1. The £5 million brought forward into the 2017-18 allocation was provided earlier rather than later to address cash flow issues and help universities manage any challenges arising from demographic changes, such as a drop in the number of 18-year-olds, and the initial implications of EU transition.&#10;2. An additional £5 million has been made available to HEFCW (Higher Education Funding Council for Wales) to kick-start the work on postgraduate support until they can fully implement Diamond at the postgraduate level. This funding is also at the discretion of universities.&#10;3. These funds are being used to mitigate the freeze in tuition fees, but no specific details were provided in the transcript regarding how this money will be spent or allocated among institutions." />
    <node id="1. The primary concern for higher education institutions and businesses is the lack of guarantee for funding beyond 2020 if a transition deal or agreement with the EU is not secured. This is because the current funding commitment from the Government only extends to 2020, and there is no assurance that it will be continued if there is no reciprocal arrangement with the EU.&#10;2. Eluned Morgan AM expressed concern about the n+2 issue beyond 2020, as there is a risk that funding might not be agreed upon by the EU or the UK Government. The expectation is that the Government will respect its pledges and commitments to fund higher education institutions after 2020.&#10;3. Llyr Gruffydd AM mentioned concerns about how this uncertainty could impact agreements between institutions and providers, as well as business decisions related to collaboration with universities. Both Eluned Morgan AM and Kirsty Williams AM have been actively involved in discussions regarding the impact of Brexit on higher and further education, emphasizing their close collaboration with the sector and student voice representatives to prepare for a potential 'no deal' Brexit scenario." />
    <node id="1. The £3.5 million funding allocation was provided to the Global Wales initiative to support them in beefing up international work and international student recruitment, as a response to the challenges and uncertainties brought about by Brexit. However, the exact number of students this funding is expected to attract has not been specified in the transcript, as it is still subject to ongoing negotiations with Universities Wales before any contracts are let." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is investing £10 million to emphasize the importance of aligning Further Education (FE) courses with employer needs, which has helped to focus the sector on responding to demands from businesses. This investment encourages FE institutions to provide courses that address skills gaps and meet specific employer requirements.&#10;&#10;2. A review of how FE is funded is currently in progress, which may lead to changes in the way FE courses are funded. If this review results in greater resources being directed towards courses that align with identified skills gaps and employer needs, it will further support the alignment of FE provision with the demands of the economy.&#10;&#10;3. The Welsh Government is engaging closely with the FE sector, student voice representatives, and employers to promote a constructive discussion around the alignment of FE courses with employer needs. This engagement ensures that Wales's institutions are open for business and welcome both EU and international students.&#10;&#10;4. While there is no specific mention of visits to FE institutions in the transcripts, it can be inferred that similar engagements and preparations are taking place for FE institutions as those described for HE institutions. This proactive approach aims to maintain learning opportunities within the FE sector in a 'no deal' Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;5. The Welsh Government is gathering information about the impact of ESF funding on FE institutions compared to HE institutions through one-to-one engagement and discussions with FE colleges. This information will help them understand how to best support FE institutions post-Brexit, ensuring their readiness for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Welsh Government is taking several measures to ensure that further education provision aligns with the needs of the economy and employer demands, including:&#10;- Investing £10 million to encourage FE institutions to respond to employer demands&#10;- Reviewing how FE is funded, potentially directing more resources towards courses aligned with identified skills gaps and employer needs&#10;- Engaging in constructive discussions with the FE sector, student voice representatives, and employers&#10;- Preparing for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario by gathering information about ESF funding impacts on FE institutions and engaging with relevant parties to understand potential implications." />
    <edge source="1. Kirsty Williams AM has been actively advocating for a separate immigration policy for international students, arguing that they should not be included in general immigration targets. She believes that the British public does not consider international students as immigrants, and therefore, their inclusion in such targets is unnecessary.&#10;2. She has campaigned for post-study work visas to be made available to more institutions outside of the south-east of England, including Cardiff and Trinity Saint David.&#10;3. The Welsh Government has also worked with Universities Wales on a specific piece of work concerning immigration policy, primarily focusing on the workforce rather than students.&#10;4. Kirsty Williams AM is aware that international students from outside the EU make up a more significant proportion of non-UK students in their institutions and considers it essential to support the recruitment and inclusion of these students." target="aker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Okay. Well, with regard to immigration, clearly, this is something, at the moment, that is out of our hands, and I have to say, it hasn't got off to a great start when initially the post-study work visas were issued just for a number of institutions in the south-east of England, with no consultation with us and I don't believe with the Scottish Government either. So, we have campaigned, pushed, cajoled, lobbied, and I was very glad that in December last year, the Home Office did then make that scheme available to Cardiff and to Trinity Saint David. We continue to press the point that we do not believe that, first of all, international students should be included in any immigration targets. I think all the evidence suggests that the British public don't regard international students as immigrants, and therefore we do need to make sure that they are taken out of the targets and we can continue to press that message with the UK Government. At the moment, you'll be aware that Welsh Government has looked at a specific piece of work on whether there was any scope for specific immigration policy for Wales, although I must say that was mostly in the field of actually the workforce rather than students.">
