    <edge source="Based on the transcript, John Griffiths AM asked if maintaining at least the current level of funding would be guaranteed if the promises made during the Brexit referendum are kept. Eluned Morgan AM indicated that this would be a minimum, but there are other aspects to consider as well. The specific amount of funding was not mentioned in the transcript. Therefore, it is not possible to provide a precise amount for the expected funding. Moreover, the adequacy of this funding to address concerns about the shared prosperity fund is also not addressed in the transcript." target="1. The primary concern for higher education institutions and businesses is the lack of guarantee for funding beyond 2020 if a transition deal or agreement with the EU is not secured. This is because the current funding commitment from the Government only extends to 2020, and there is no assurance that it will be continued if there is no reciprocal arrangement with the EU.&#10;2. The prospect of a 'no deal' Brexit scenario would allow higher education institutions in Wales to charge international fees to students from the EU, as the UK government has control over its own immigration policy and can set different fee levels for students coming from different countries. However, if a deal is reached with the EU that establishes the principle of reciprocal arrangements, this ability would be curtailed.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is working closely with the higher education sector and student voice representatives to prepare for a potential 'no deal' Brexit scenario, ensuring that Wales's institutions are open for business and welcome both EU and international students. They are also improving international marketing of the HE sector, accessing resources under the European Transition Fund, Global Wales program, and other opportunities within the EU transition pot of money to boost international marketing of the HE sector and highlight its strengths.&#10;4. The impact of Brexit on hi