    <edge source="1. Based on the transcript, the Welsh Government has not provided a specific funding commitment for the implementation of the Diamond and Reid reviews. However, Kirsty Williams AM has stated that the Welsh Government is fully committed to implementing the Diamond review proposals and has had discussions with HEFCW about their expectations for the implementation of Diamond. With regard to Reid, she mentioned that ongoing discussions are taking place within the government regarding the implementation of its recommendations. While they have not made a specific funding commitment, Kirsty Williams AM emphasized their commitment to implementing the Diamond review proposals and their intention to provide resources to institutions, as proposed by Diamond." target="1. Based on the transcript, there are several challenges faced by institutions regarding their financial planning:&#10;&#10;a. Lack of specific funding commitment from the Welsh Government for the implementation of the Diamond and Reid reviews - While Kirsty Williams AM has stated that the government is committed to implementing the Diamond review proposals, she did not make a specific funding commitment. Regarding Reid, she mentioned ongoing discussions within the government regarding its recommendations.&#10;&#10;b. Impact of Brexit - The transcript suggests that there are uncertainties around the impact of Brexit on higher education institutions, particularly regarding their exposure to EU students and potential changes in funding opportunities like Horizon 2020.&#10;&#10;c. Revenue generation - Institutions need to raise some of their own money, as mentioned by Eluned Morgan AM. Suzy Davies AM also highlights that these institutions are interested in revenue because it supports the staff.&#10;&#10;d. Employment precarity - The transcript mentions that employment opportunities today have a transitional nature and people are not getting the kind of contracts they'd like, making their lives very precarious. This situation may lead to less commitment from staff members.&#10;&#10;2. To become more responsive to employers' needs for skills in their areas, institutions can:&#10;&#10;a. Foster better relationships with employers - Eluned Morgan AM suggests that there is room for institutions to be more proactive and engaged with employers.&#10;&#10;b. Develop tailored programs based on the need for skills - By understanding the specific demands of local industries, institutions can design courses and training programs that better equip students for available jobs.&#10;&#10;c. Increase flexibility in program offerings - To adapt quickly to changing employer needs, institutions may need to review their current curriculum and consider offering more short-term or modular courses, enabling quicker updates based on industry demands.">
