ration policy and the setting of different fee levels for students coming from different countries.&#10;&#10;3. Risk assessment and mitigation: The Higher Education Funding Council for Wales (HEFCW) has conducted specific risk assessment and mitigation work regarding Brexit, although the extent of sharing this information publicly is at their discretion.&#10;&#10;4. Proactive institution visits: Welsh officials have been visiting individual higher education institutions (HEIs) to discuss their preparedness for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario, ensuring they have plans in place to deal with various potential outcomes.&#10;&#10;5. International marketing and research funding: The Welsh Government has collaborated with Universities Wales and student voice representatives to improve international marketing of the HE sector, access resources under the European Transition Fund, Global Wales program, and other EU transition pot opportunities to strengthen the sector's competitiveness in research funding, regardless of a deal or no-deal Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;6. Addressing issues related to Erasmus+ provision, Horizon 2020 impacts, and UK stand-alone projects: Welsh officials have been working with Westminster counterparts to tackle issues related to Erasmus+ provision, Horizon 2020 impacts, and UK stand-alone projects in the event of a 'no deal' Brexit.&#10;&#10;7. Comprehensive understanding of potential challenges: The Welsh Government has conducted its own analysis on the impact of Brexit on HE, FE, and apprenticeship provision, complementing Cardiff University's research with Bevan Foundation and others to provide a comprehensive understanding of potential challenges.&#10;&#10;8. Separate immigration policy for international students: Kirsty Williams AM is actively pushing for a separate immigration policy for international students, arguing that they should not be included in general immigration targets. She has also campaigned for post-study work visas to be made available to more institutions outside of the south-east of England, including Cardiff and Trinity Saint David.&#10;&#10;9. Maintaining quality of faculty: NUS and students are concerned about maintaining the quality of faculty in higher education institutions, valuing the diversity and strength that EU staff bring to these institutions. They want assurance that there will be no negative impact on this valuable contribution and are working towards providing security and stability for EU staff.&#10;&#10;10. Funding security for European students: NUS and students also value diversity in the student population and want to ensure that European students feel secure about their funding for the next academic year, despite the uncertainty caused by Brexit.&#10;&#10;11. Participation in higher education schemes: NUS has launched a powerful campaign emphasizing the importance of Erasmus+ arrangements for Welsh students and young people, promoting participation in beneficial schemes like Erasmus+.">
