er needs. This engagement ensures that Wales's institutions are open for business and welcome both EU and international students.&#10;&#10;4. While there is no specific mention of visits to FE institutions in the transcripts, it can be inferred that similar engagements and preparations are taking place for FE institutions as those described for HE institutions. This proactive approach aims to maintain learning opportunities within the FE sector in a 'no deal' Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;5. The Welsh Government is gathering information about the impact of ESF funding on FE institutions compared to HE institutions through one-to-one engagement and discussions with FE colleges. This information will help them understand how to best support FE institutions post-Brexit, ensuring their readiness for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Welsh Government is taking several measures to ensure that further education provision aligns with the needs of the economy and employer demands, including:&#10;- Investing £10 million to encourage FE institutions to respond to employer demands&#10;- Reviewing how FE is funded, potentially directing more resources towards courses aligned with identified skills gaps and employer needs&#10;- Engaging in constructive discussions with the FE sector, student voice representatives, and employers&#10;- Preparing for a 'no deal' Brexit scenario by gathering information about ESF funding impacts on FE institutions and engaging with relevant parties to understand potential implications.">
